AUTHENTICATION METHODS
1. ACCESS TOKEN(ACOUNT KEY) - A secret key that gives full access to the storage account.
        spark.conf.set(
        "fs.azure.account.key.<storage>.dfs.core.windows.net",
        "ACCESS_KEY"
        )

        🔹 Pros
        ✔ Easy to use
        ✔ Full access
        🔹 Cons ❌
        ❌ Very risky (full control)
        ❌ Hard to manage securely
        ❌ Not recommended for production

2. SAS TOKEN - A temporary, limited access token to storage.[Like giving someone a temporary pass with limited permissions]
        spark.conf.set(
        "fs.azure.sas.<container>.<storage>.dfs.core.windows.net",
        "SAS_TOKEN"
        )
        🔹 Example permissions
        Read only
        Write only
        Valid for specific time

        🔹 Pros
        ✔ Secure (limited access)
        ✔ Time-based expiry
        ✔ Fine-grained permissions
        🔹 Cons
        ❌ Still needs token management
        ❌ Can be exposed if not handled properly

3. RBAC[ROLE BASE ACCESS CONTROL] - Access is controlled by assigning roles to users/services [Instead of keys, access is managed through identity (who you are).]
        🔹 Example roles
        Storage Blob Data Reader
        Storage Blob Data Contributor

        🔹 Pros
        ✔ Most ecure ✅
        ✔ No secrets to manage
        ✔ Scalable & enterprise-ready
        ✔ Integrated with Azure AD
        🔹 Cons
        ❌ Initial setup is complex

| Feature      | Access Key  | SAS Token        | RBAC                  |
| ------------ | ----------- | ---------------- | --------------------- |
| Access Level | Full access | Limited          | Role-based            |
| Security     | ❌ Low      | ⚠️ Medium       | ✅ High               |
| Expiry       | ❌ No       | ✅ Yes          | ❌ No (identity-based)|
| Use Case     | Testing     | Temporary access | Production            |

