            JOINS

🔹 Sample Tables
👨‍💼 Employees table
emp_id	name	dept_id
1	Arun	10
2	Ravi	20
3	Meena	30
4	John	40

🏢 Departments table
dept_id	dept_name
10	IT
20	HR
30	Finance
50	Admin


1. inner join - only matching rows from the both table

    SELECT e.emp_id, e.name, d.dept_name
    FROM employees e
    INNER JOIN departments d
    ON e.dept_id = d.dept_id;

    Output
    emp_id	name	dept_name
    1	Arun	IT
    2	Ravi	HR
    3	Meena	Finance
    👉 John is removed (no matching dept)
    When to use:
    ✔ When you only want valid relationships
    ✔ No NULL/unknown data needed

2. left join - returns all the rows from the left table with matching rows from the right table. rows without a match are filled with nulls. this is also called as left outer join

    SELECT e.emp_id, e.name, d.dept_name
    FROM employees e
    LEFT JOIN departments d
    ON e.dept_id = d.dept_id;

    Output
    emp_id	name	dept_name
    1	Arun	IT
    2	Ravi	HR
    3	Meena	Finance
    4	John	NULL
    👉 John has no department → still included
    When to use:
    ✔ When LEFT table is your main data
    ✔ When you want to find missing matches

3. right join -- opposite to left join

    SELECT e.emp_id, e.name, d.dept_name
    FROM employees e
    LEFT JOIN departments d
    ON e.dept_id = d.dept_id;

    Output
    emp_id	name	dept_name
    1	Arun	IT
    2	Ravi	HR
    3	Meena	Finance
    4	John	NULL
    👉 Admin department has no employees

4. full outer join -- it returns all the rows from left and right tables. it fill null for not matching rows

    SELECT e.emp_id, e.name, d.dept_name
    FROM employees e
    FULL OUTER JOIN departments d
    ON e.dept_id = d.dept_id;

    Output
    emp_id	name	dept_name
    1	Arun	IT
    2	Ravi	HR
    3	Meena	Finance
    4	John	NULL
    NULL	NULL	Admin

5. cross join - returns all the possible combinations of rows from the left and right tables
    🔹 Simple Idea
    Think of it like:
    👕 T-shirts × 👖 Pants
    👉 Every T-shirt is paired with every Pant

    CROSS JOIN Query
    SELECT color, size
    FROM colors
    CROSS JOIN sizes;

    🔹 Output
    color	size
    Red 	S
    Red	    M
    Red	    L
    Blue	S
    Blue	M
    Blue	L

    🔥 What happened?
    2 colors × 3 sizes = 6 rows
    Every combination is created

